      <hedline>
        <hl1>Reward Good Teachers</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Jack M Pollock reply to May 1 letter backs merit pay for teachers</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>A May 1 letter objects to basing teachers' merit pay on test scores because of the incentives for cheating that would be created. But there are other ways to measure teacher merit.  Classroom performance and scholarship may be evaluated by supervisors, committees or outside agencies.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>A May 1 letter objects to basing teachers' merit pay on test scores because of the incentives for cheating that would be created. But there are other ways to measure teacher merit.  Classroom performance and scholarship may be evaluated by supervisors, committees or outside agencies.</p>
        <p>Studies in Colorado and elsewhere suggest that merit pay would raise the quality of education. In any event, it is time we abandoned the fiction that all teachers are equally qualified and equally effective. Why should the worst teachers be paid the same as the best?</p>
        <p>JACK M. POLLOCK  New York, May 1, 2000</p>
      </block>
